The core functionality of `UploadCountClient` moved pretty much as-is.  Instead of wrapping a Future around the operation, the code opts to wrap it in an Rx `Single` indicating that this is a single-shot operation that will emit a single successful result or a failure (rather than a stream of values that you would get from an `Observable`)
```java
public Single<Integer> getUploadCount(final String userName) {
    return Single.create(new SingleOnSubscribe<Integer>() {
        @Override
        public void subscribe(@NonNull SingleEmitter<Integer> emitter) throws Exception {
            URL url;
            try {
                url = new URL(String.format(Locale.ENGLISH, UPLOAD_COUNT_URL_TEMPLATE,
                        new PageTitle(userName).getText()));
                HttpURLConnection urlConnection = (HttpURLConnection) url.openConnection();
                try {
                    BufferedReader bufferedReader = new BufferedReader(new
                            InputStreamReader(urlConnection.getInputStream()));
                    String uploadCount = bufferedReader.readLine();
                    bufferedReader.close();
                    emitter.onSuccess(Integer.parseInt(uploadCount));
                } finally {
                    urlConnection.disconnect();
                }
            } catch (Throwable e) {
                Timber.e("Error getting upload count", e);
            }
        }
    });
}
```

